{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"759ba90e-ad00-4255-9a86-742ebe7c4de7","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace with a `stdio` transport that runs your project:\n\n```jsonc\n// .vscode/mcp.json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — uses `dotnet run` so the project is built and launched automatically.\n- For a published build, replace with `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` (the compiled executable).\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout using the MCP protocol (e.g., via the `ModelContextProtocol` or `Microsoft.Extensions.AI` SDK).\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will detect the server. You can verify it's connected in the **MCP: List Servers** command palette entry.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"826dfc3f-c35d-41d9-8ef6-489d60ec2670","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist, but the user is asking how to configure mcp.json, not asking me to build anything. I can answer this directly.","outputTokens":326,"requestId":"8436:1B0168:104CF8D:145AD54:69FFDAEF"},"id":"d9e2a204-1fbc-4168-bfb9-a258350d8625","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:10:15.341Z","parentId":"b9ea1dbf-d0c6-4685-94f1-17bc7a5fa7bd"}
